    i) Bubble sort
        Bubble Sort is a simple sorting algorithm .they repeatedly compares two target elements,
and swaps them if they are in the wrong order.
This process continues until the entire array is sorted,It is called Bubble Sort .

#ALGORITHM
1 Start with first element
2 Compare these with next element
3 then first element is greater, swap it
4 Continue comparing adjacent elements up to the end of the array
5 Repeate the process for the remaining unsorted part
6 Stop when no more swaps it is complete
7 finish the sorting

* Space Complexity
O(1) (uses constant extra memory)

#Advantages
i Easy to understand and implement
ii Suitable for small datasets

#Disadvantages
i Slow for large datasets
ii Performs many unnecessary comparisons and swaps


    ii)  Selection sort
    Selection Sort is a simple sorting algorithm that repeatedly finds the smallest element from the 
unsorted part of the array and places it at the beginning.

#ALGORITHM
1 Start with first element
2 Find the smallest element in the unsorted part
3 Swap it with the first unsorted element
4 go to the sorted value on one position to the right
5 Repeat until the array is sorted
6 finish the sorting

* Space Complexity
O(1) (constant extra memory)

#Advantages
i Easy to understand and implement
ii Uses fewer swaps than Bubble Sort
iii Works well for small datasets

#Disadvantages
i Slow for large datasets
ii Less efficient than Merge Sort or Quick Sort


    iii)Insertion Sort
Insertion Sort is a simple sorting method where elements are sorted by inserting each element into 
its correct position in the already sorted part of the array,It works arranging playing cards in your hands.

#ALGORITHM
1 Assume first element is sorted.
2 take the next element (value).
3 Compare with elements in the sorted part.
4 Shift bigger elements one position to the right.
5 Insert the value in the correct position.
6 Repeat for all elements.
7 finish the sorting

*Space Complexity
O(1) (in-place sorting)

#Advantages
i Very efficient for small sorted arrays
ii Simple to implement.
iii Works in real-time (data comes one by one)

#Disadvantages
i Slow for large datasets
ii Requires shifting of elements (costly for big arrays)


    iii)Merge Sort

Merge Sort is a Divide and Conquer sorting algorithm. It divides the array 
into smaller halves, sorts each half, and then merges the sorted halves into one sorted array.

#ALGORITHM
1 Divide the array into two parts.
2 sort the left half
3 sort the right half.
4 Merge the two sorted oarts.
5 Repeat process the entire array is sorted
6 finish the sorting.

Space Complexity
O(n) (extra memory is needed for merging)

Advantages
i Fast and efficient for large datasets
ii Stable sorting 

Disadvantages
i Requires extra memory (O(n)).
ii More complex than Bubble, Selection, or Insertion Sort


iii)Quick Sort 
Quick Sort is a fast sorting algorithm based on Divide and Conquer,
It selects a pivot element, then arranges elements into two parts.

#ALGORITHM
1 Choose a pivot element
2 Divide array into two parts
3 smaller than pivot
4 greater than pivot
5 Recursively apply Quick Sort on both parts
6 Combine results
7 finish sorting

Space Complexity
O(log n) (recursive stack)
Worst case: O(n)

Advantages
i Very fast in practice
ii Requires less extra memory than Merge Sort
iii Good for large datasets

Disadvantages
i Worst case is O(n²)
ii Not stable (does not preserve order of equal elements)
iii Performance depends on pivot selection
